{{// @category Preferences }}
{{// @tooltip Heightened, cinematic. Genre conventions apply. Dramatic timing over realism. }}
{{// @color #9B59B6 }}
{{// @icon ✨ }}

{{setvar::WorldLogicLabel::Genre Logic}}

{{setvar::WorldLogic::## ✨ Genre Logic

**The genre is the physics engine.**

The world operates by the internal rules of its genre, not by real-world constraints. Accept these conventions without justification or apology.}}

{{trim}}

{{// @category Preferences }}
{{// @tooltip Anime/manga conventions. Emotional physics, power systems, sincere dramatic declaration, flashback mechanics. }}
{{// @color #E91E8C }}
{{// @icon ⚡ }}

{{setvar::WorldLogicLabel::Anime}}

{{setvar::WorldLogic::## ⚡ Anime

**The world runs on emotional physics.**

Emotional intensity is the engine that drives everything. When a character reaches their limit — when their conviction burns hot enough — the world responds. Rules bend. Limits shatter. Power answers feeling. Write with that logic fully intact and fully sincere.

- **Emotion has mechanical force.** Willpower, desperation, love, rage, and resolve are not motivations — they are power sources. A character who refuses to fall gets back up, and the narrative treats that refusal as a real force acting on the world. When someone names their reason for fighting, they hit harder. This is not metaphor. This is how the physics work here.
- **Power scales with arc.** Characters grow stronger through training, loss, and confrontation with their own limits. A rival who once seemed impossible becomes beatable after a character confronts what held them back. Power levels are real, but they shift when the story demands transformation.
- **Archetypes are real roles.** The rival who pushes the protagonist past their ceiling. The mentor who hides their true strength until the moment it matters. The villain who was once an idealist and broke. These are structural positions, filled with sincerity.
- **Flashbacks are combat mechanics.** A memory surfacing mid-fight is not a pacing break — it is the moment a character unlocks what they need. The recalled promise fuels the final strike.
- **Dramatic declaration is sincere.** When a character names their technique or speaks their conviction aloud before striking — that is ritual. It is how power is shaped and channeled in this world. Treat it with full gravity.}}

{{trim}}

{{// @category Preferences }}
{{// @tooltip RPG/game logic. Stats exist, death has rules, NPCs have roles, quests are real. }}
{{// @color #27AE60 }}
{{// @icon 🎮 }}

{{setvar::WorldLogicLabel::Game Logic}}

{{setvar::WorldLogic::## 🎮 Video Game

**The world is structured like a game, and it knows it.**

Characters exist in a world with systems. Stats, skills, levels, loot, quests — these are real features of the reality, whether characters acknowledge them or simply live inside their constraints.

- **Characters have builds.** Every character has strengths, weaknesses, and specializations functioning like stat distributions. A stealth build cannot brute-force a combat encounter without consequence. Respect the build. Choices close some doors and open others.
- **Progression is real.** Characters get stronger, gain new abilities, unlock access to harder content. Early-game enemies become trivial. Late-game threats are genuinely beyond current capability until the character grows into them. Experience is earned through action.
- **Death has rules.** Whether the world uses respawn, save states, or permadeath — establish the rule and hold to it. If death is a setback, it carries cost. If death is final, it is final.
- **Quests structure the world.** Objectives exist. They have stages: accepted, in progress, completed, failed. NPCs offer them. Rewards follow completion. Side quests pull in unexpected directions. Quest logs are real — characters know what they need to do.
- **Loot and inventory matter.** Items have value, function, and rarity. A locked chest in an empty room is content, not decoration. Resource management is a real constraint.
- **The world is zoned.** Areas have themes, difficulty curves, and environmental identity. The starting village feels different from the endgame fortress. Crossing into a new zone is a felt transition.}}

